  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1299121/files/Sensitivity.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00003 Point source (5-sigma) sensitivity for 48 hr (solar time) observation at 30$^{\circ}$ off-axis of the GAMMA-LIGHT GRID imager (in red color). Also shown are the Fermi-LAT Pass7V6 sensitivity (total-LAT: black color; front-LAT: blue color) and AGILE's sensitivity (gray) for the same duration.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1299121/files/Time_vsEn.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00007 Timeline schedule versus the energy range covered by present and future detectors in X and gamma-ray astrophysics.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1299121/files/W44.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00006 The gamma-ray spectrum of one of the most prominent gamma-ray emitting SNRs showing a clear signature of neutral pion decay, W44. The Fermi (green triangles) and AGILE (red diamonds) data are shown. The spectral modeling involves a component due to the neutral pion decay (yellow line) plus a component due to Bremsstrahlung (blue line). The red curve shows the expected GAMMA-LIGHT sensitivity for a 1-year effective time integration.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="856" ind1="4" ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="u">http://inspirehep.net/record/1299121/files/angres.png</subfield>
    <subfield code="y">00001 Point Spread Function (PSF, 68$\%$ containment radius) of the GAMMA-LIGHT gamma-ray (GRID) imager (in red color) obtained by extensive GEANT-4 simulations which assume an incidence angle of 30$^{\circ}$, Silicon strip analog readout, and Kalman filter analysis of particle tracks. For comparison, we show the Fermi-LAT Pass7V6 PSF (total LAT: blue curve; front-LAT: black color) and the AGILE PSF (in gray color).</subfield>
  </datafield>
